'''American Airlines Flight 1''' was a domestic, scheduled passenger flight from [[Idlewild Airport]], [[New York]] to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] that crashed shortly after take-off on {{date|March 1, 1962}}. All 87 passengers and 8 crew died in the crash. At the time, it was the deadliest accident in the United States. A [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] (CAB) investigation determined that a manufacturing defect in the automatic pilot system led to mechanical failure, which caused the accident. 

A number of notable people lost their lives in the crash, including oilman [[W. Alton Jones]]; Admiral [[Richard Lansing Conolly]], president of [[Long Island University]]; and [[Arnold Kirkeby]], realtor. At the time, Flight 1 was the deadliest aviation accident to occur on US soil. It was the sixth fatal Boeing 707 crash, and, at the time, the deadliest. As of {{date|December 1, 2009}}, American Airlines Flight 1 still services the nonstop [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]]-[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles LAX]] route, albeit with a [[Boeing 767]]-223ER.

== Flight ==
The aircraft was a [[Boeing 707]]-123B, U.S. Registry N 7506A. It was manufactured on {{date|February 12, 1959}}, and was delivered to [[American Airlines]] on that same day. At the time of the crash, it had accumulated 8,147 hours of air time during the course of 3 years. Its last periodic inspection had occurred on {{date|January 18, 1962}} at 7,922 hours of air time.<ref name="cab" /> The flight crew consisted of Captain James T. Heist, First Officer Michael Barna, Jr., Second Officer Robert J. Pecor, and Flight Engineer Robert J. Cain. Also aboard were four stewardesses: Shirley Grabow, Lois Kelly, Betty Moore, and Rosalind Stewart.<ref name="cab">{{cite conference
| date = January 15, 1963
| title = American Airlines, Inc., Boeing 707-123B N 7506A, Jamaica Bay, Long Island, New York, March 1, 1962
| id = Docket No. SA-366. File No. 1-0001
| publisher = Civil Aeronautics Board
| url = http://ntl1.specialcollection.net/scripts/ws.dll?file&fn=8&name=*S%3A\DOT_56GB\airplane%20accidents\websearch\030162.pdf
| format = PDf
| accessdate = 2009-11-21
}}<br /><small>(Navigate: Historical Aircraft Accident Reports (1934-1965)<U+2192> 1962<U+2192> American Airlines)</small></ref>

The aircraft received instructions to taxi to [[Idlewild Airport|Idlewild]]'s Runway 31L at 09:54 AM EST, and clearance to proceed to Los Angeles non-stop under [[instrument flight rules]] (IFR) at 10:02 AM EST. Flight 1 became airborne at 10:07 AM EST. Following American Airlines procedures and Departure Control instructions, the aircraft initiated a left-ward turn.<ref name="cab" /> In the course of the turn, the Boeing [[flight dynamics|banked]] too far, flipped 90 degrees, and began an upside-down, nose-first descent in a nearly vertical dive.<ref name="cab" />

Flight 1 crashed into Pumpkin Patch Channel, [[Jamaica Bay]], at 10:08:49.<ref name="cab" /> Passengers aboard a plane bound for [[Albany, New York|Albany]] that took off immediately after Flight 1 could only watch, horrified, as the airliner plunged to its fiery demise.<ref name="time-1962-3-9">{{cite news
 | title = Disasters: Tragedy in Jamaica Bay
 | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939941,00.html
 | newspaper = [[Time Magazine|Time]]
 | date = March 9, 1962
 | accessdate = 2009-11-22
 }}</ref><ref name="review-1962-3-2" /> The jet exploded upon impact, a geyser of [[brackish water]] and black smoke erupting from the site, and the scattered debris and fuel caught fire.<ref name="time-1962-3-9" /> Long Island residents described hearing explosions which shook the foundations of nearby houses, though no one is known to have actually witnessed the crash.<ref name="star-1962-3-1">{{cite news
 | title = 95 Are Believed Dead in Crash of Jet Airliner
 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EwURAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6ucDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5918,3765859
 | format = PDF
 | agency = AP
 | newspaper = The Free-Lance Star 
 | location = Fredericksburg, VA
 | date = March 1, 1962
 | pages = 1, 3
 | accessdate = 2009-11-22
 }} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/craft-goes-down-in-marsh-off-short-of-long-island/ plaintext])</ref><ref name="review-1962-3-2">{{cite news
 | title = Tides Hampering Hunt for Victims
 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uqQRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FegDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6322,563321
 | format = PDF
 | agency = AP
 | newspaper = The Spokesman-Review
 | location = Spokane, WA
 | date = March 2, 1962
 | page = 1
 | accessdate = 2009-11-22
