== Investigation ==
The aircraft crashed into a remote area of [[marsh]]land on Jamaica Bay used as a wildlife sanctuary.<ref name="review-1962-3-2" /> Upwards of 300 policemen and fire fighters, including 125 detectives attending a narcotics seminar at the Police Academy, as well as [[US Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] helicopters were mobilized to the crash site within half an hour of the crash for rescue operations, only to find that there were no survivors.<ref name="star-1962-3-1" /><ref name="review-1962-3-2" /> The three-alarm fire was under control by 10:50 AM EST, by which point only wreckage remained.<ref name="star-1962-3-1" /> Low tides aided search personnel in their attempts to salvage bodies from the downed aircraft. Only a few bodies remained intact.<ref name="review-1962-3-2" />

Investigators were unable to recover sufficient body tissue to determine whether the crew had been physically incapacitated at the time of the crash.<ref name="cab" /> Toxicology reports conclusively ruled out toxic gases, alcohol and drugs as possible cause for the crash.<ref name="cab" /> Milton Helpern, Chief Medical Examiner, decided that having relatives attempt visual identification of the crash victims was inhumane, and ordered dental and fingerprint comparisons.<ref name="time-1962-3-9" /> In early July, the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] announced their investigators believed that a [[split pin|cotter pin]] and a [[bolt]] missing from the rudder mechanism might have caused the crash of Flight 1. Though considered to be a "mechanic's oversight," the FAA nevertheless wired all 707 operators to inform them of the potential danger of the assembly.<ref name="star-1962-6-13">{{cite news |title= Lost Bolt May Have Casued Crash|first= Walter R.|last= Mears|url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9XcQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QIwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6301,5138019|format= PDF|agency= AP|newspaper= The Free-Lance Star|location= Fredericksburg, VA|date= June 13, 1962|page= 8|accessdate= 2009-11-20}} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/lost-bolt-may-have-caused-crash/ plaintext])</ref>

The [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] received notification of the accident at 10:10 AM EST and immediately sent investigators to Jamaica Bay to conduct an investigation. The flight recorder was found on March 9 and sent to Washington for analysis.<ref name="banner-1962-3-9">{{cite news
 | title = Flight Recorder of Ill-Fated Plane Found
 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ezIaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uw4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2843,1575115
 | format = PDF
 | agency = AP
 | newspaper = Ocala Star-Banner 
 | location = Ocala, FL
 | date = March 9, 1962
 | page = 7
 | accessdate = 2009-11-22
 }} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/flight-recorder-of-ill-fated-plane-found/ plaintext])</ref> Public hearings were held at the International Hotel in New York on March 20-23, 1962.<ref name="cab" /> In January 1963, the [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] released a report stating that the "most likely abnormality" to have caused the crash was a short circuit caused by wires in the automatic piloting system that had been damaged in the manufacturing process. FAA inspectors had inspected units at a [[Teterboro, New Jersey]] [[Bendix Corporation]] plant and discovered workers using tweezers to bind up bundles of wires, thereby damaging them.<ref name="guard-1963-1-15">{{cite news |title= CAB Blames Jet Crash on Short Circuit|url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qiYRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=O-kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3856,2415003|format= PDF|agency= AP|newspaper= Eugene Register-Guard|location= Eugene, OR|date= January 15, 1963|page= 1|accessdate= 2009-11-21 }} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/cab-blames-jet-crash-on-short-circuit/ plaintext])</ref> The Bendix Corporation issued denials, stating that the units underwent 61 inspections during manufacturing, in addition to inspections during installation and maintenance work, and insisted that had the protective coating of the wires been breached at some point it would have surely been caught and the unit replaced.<ref name="gazette-1963-1-16">{{cite news |title= CAB Blames Tweezers for 95-Death Crash|url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uT4NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HmwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4868,2102670|format= PDf|agency= AP|newspaper= Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|location= Pittsburgh, PA|date= January 16, 1963|page= 2|accessdate= 2009-11-21}} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/cab-blames-tweezers-for-95-death-crash/ plaintext])</ref>

At the time, Flight 1 was the deadliest aviation accident to occur on US soil. It was the sixth fatal Boeing 707 crash, and, at the time, the deadliest.<ref name="asn">{{ASN accident|id=19620301-0|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> As of December 2009, American Airlines Flight 1 operates a nonstop 9:00 AM [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]]-[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles LAX]] route, albeit with a [[Boeing 767]]-223ER.<ref>{{Cite book
  | title = American Airlines Worldwide Timetable
  | page = 32
  | publisher = American Airlines
  | location = Dallas/Fort Worth, Texas
  | date = December 1, 2009
  | url = http://www.aatimetable.com/aa.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate = 2009-12-8}}</ref>

== Notable victims ==
A number of notable people were aboard Flight 1 when it met its fiery demise in Jamaica Bay.<ref name="review-1962-3-2b">{{cite news
 | title = Noted Men Lose Lives In Crash
 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uqQRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FegDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6322,563321
 | format = PDF
 | agency = AP
 | newspaper = The Spokesman-Review
 | location = Spokane, WA
 | date = March 2, 1962
 | page = 1
 | accessdate = 2009-11-22
 }} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/noted-men-lose-lives-in-crash/ plaintext])</ref> They included:

* '''[[W. Alton Jones]]''', multi-millionaire former president of [[Cities Service Company]] (now [[CITGO]]) and close personal friend of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].

* '''John Dieckman''', international champion flyfisher and caster.

* '''Admiral [[Richard Lansing Conolly]]''', [[US Navy|USN]] ret., president of [[Long Island University]] and two-time Deputy [[Chief of Naval Operations]].

* '''[[Arnold Kirkeby]]''', millionaire realtor and former head of the Kirkeby chain of luxury hotels.

* '''Irving Rubine''', film producer of [[The Guns of Navarone (film)|The Guns of Navarone]].

* '''[[Louise Lindner|Louise Lindner Eastman]]''', whose daughter [[Linda McCartney|Linda Eastman]] would later marry the [[The Beatles|Beatle]] [[Paul McCartney]].

In addition, 15 abstract paintings by the late [[artist]] [[Arshile Gorky]] were en route to Los Angeles for an exhibition and were destroyed. Alton Jones was found to be carrying $55,690 in cash, including a $10,000-bill.<ref name="time-1962-3-9" />

